help please k so i have a one year old husky puppy these past few days whenever i leave home she tears up the house she didnt used to do this she shreds up newspapers and books anything she can find its becoming a habit and i cant deal with cleaning up the mess every single time i think its a cry for attention because lately ive been extremely busy with no time for her could that be the reason or why else how can i stop this i dont want to give her away help please she is experiencing separation anxiety huskies are very active dogs and very social animals she is not used to being alone and is dealing with her frustration by tearing things up i had a ridgeback that decided to tear up my house one day when i left her home she was only months old and literally destroyed a bedroom her breed designates the need for lots of exercise she comes from a working breed and designed for miles of running sled pulling etc you need to walk her run her let her pull you via skis skates or whatever daily get it exercise her before starting any training activity this will allow her to release any frustration she may already have and make your training session better to help with her anxiety you will need to train her to deal with you being away thru conditioning also i suggest you keep her in a room or area where she cannot tear chew or possibly swallow something that could hurt her or worse keep toys on hand for her and let her know these things are ok for her to chew and tear up give her praise and play with her when she does play and chew these items this will let her know it's ok leave her for a few minutes at a time in this area and then come back extending the time away from her a little at a time be sure to be close by at first incase she does act up stop her when she start acting out do not pet her or hug her during this period or you will confuse her and she will take this as positive reinforcement of her actions praise and reward her when she behaves in a positive manner start with a few minutes and build up to whatever time you need say an hour or so when she behaves in a negative way make sure you catch her to correct her by taking the article away or putting her in a calm position sitting etc be sure to stay calm and assertive during training and no yelling or screaming you give her power over you and tell her you are not the dominant leader when you do this this will take time to do and being consistent is the main key so remember exercise discipline and affection also dominant pack leaders are calm and assertive watch cesar milan on the national geographic channel and visit the website for a lot more tips good luck Dog training Dog Housebreaking Episodes of Lost (Season 1) Social rule Obedience training Shaggy dog story Alaskan husky Milton H. Erickson Mojave people Fancy rat The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe The Contender (television series) EastEnders Poker jargon The Inside Domestic rabbit Kodocha Piccolo Junior Saga Ferret Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Wild at Heart (Buffy episode) Tenshinhan Second language acquisition Time Out of Mind Indianapolis 500 Hamster Babe Ruth Main characters of Fullmetal Alchemist Iditarod God Emperor of Dune Urinary incontinence Traumatic incident reduction Garfield Appeal Piccolo (Dragon Ball) 1925 serum run to Nome Pitaten Horse Blood on the Tracks Extreme Programming Paragliding Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2005-06 Sled dog Electrophysiology The Apprentice 2 USS Sea Dog (SS-401) Pakistani cricket team in West Indies in 2005 Theory of conduct The Dalek Invasion of Earth 24 Hours of Le Mans Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban Japanese tea ceremony Scenes from a Memory USS Tunny (SS-282) StarCraft: Uprising Baseball The Death Gate Cycle Father's Day (Doctor Who) Stoicism USS Uhlmann (DD-687) Fast bowling The Star Wars Holiday Special Ben Johnson (athlete) Aerial (dance move) Columbine High School massacre Robot Wars Oh My Goddess! Spice Girls Paintball The Invisi